    "instruction": "Load metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv, and error_logs.csv from the current directory. Provide a compact summary only with the following items (no raw full tables):\\n1) Total row count for each file.\\n2) Global min(timestamp) and max(timestamp) across all files.\\n3) Unique cmdb_id values present across all files (list).\\n4) For metric.csv: list unique (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pairs with the count of rows for each pair, sorted by count descending, limited to top 20 rows.\\n5) For trace.csv: list unique (cmdb_id, trace_name) pairs with the count of rows for each pair, sorted by count descending, limited to top 20 rows.\\n6) For log.csv: list unique (cmdb_id, log_name) pairs with the count of rows for each pair, sorted by count descending, limited to top 20 rows.\\nReturn results in a JSON-serializable structure (dictionaries/lists). Do not convert timestamps to datetimes. Limit any returned lists to at most 20 entries each."}

{
    "analysis": "We have ingested a compact summary of all telemetry files: row counts, global timestamp range (1616491800–1616493600), and the list of available cmdb_id values and top (cmdb_id,KPI) pairs per file. Next, per the diagnosis workflow we should compute global thresholds for component-KPI time series before filtering to the incident window. To follow the processing order, we will first compute global thresholds for metric time series for the allowed root-cause components (the component list provided by the system). This will let us detect metric anomalies later within the incident time window. No threshold calculations have been done yet.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From metric.csv, for every (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pair where cmdb_id is one of the allowed root-cause components [apache01, apache02, Tomcat01, Tomcat02, Tomcat03, Tomcat04, MG01, MG02, IG01, IG02, Mysql01, Mysql02, Redis01, Redis02], compute the following using the full available series (do NOT filter by incident time window):\\n1) count of data points,\\n2) global P95 of the 'value' field,\\n3) global P5 of the 'value' field,\\n4) global mean of 'value'.\\nReturn a JSON-serializable list of objects with fields: cmdb_id, kpi_name, count, p95, p5, mean. Sort the list by count descending and return at most the top 20 rows. Also return a separate integer: the total number of distinct (cmdb_id,kpi_name) pairs found for these components. Limit any returned lists to at most 20 entries."}

{
    "analysis": "We computed global thresholds (P95, P5, mean) for all (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pairs of the allowed root-cause components using the full metric series. There are 1111 distinct pairs in total; top pairs by count include Tomcat thread/process/network KPIs and MG01 JVM memory/thread KPIs. These global thresholds are now available in kernel variables and must be used (not recomputed) before any incident-window filtering. Next, per the workflow, we must detect anomalies inside the incident window (the provided timestamp range 1616491800–1616493600) by comparing metric points to their global thresholds (flagging values >=P95 or <=P5). This will narrow candidate faulty component-KPIs and their earliest anomaly times for further trace/log analysis.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the previously computed global thresholds stored in the kernel (for each (cmdb_id,kpi_name) of the allowed root-cause components), filter metric.csv to timestamps within [1616491800, 1616493600] (inclusive). For each (cmdb_id,kpi_name) present in the thresholds, find metric rows in that time window where value >= global_p95 OR value <= global_p5. Produce a compact aggregate report (JSON-serializable) with:\\n1) total number of (cmdb_id,kpi_name) pairs that have at least one anomaly in the window (anomaly defined as above);\\n2) top 20 (cmdb_id,kpi_name) pairs by anomaly point count, each entry containing: cmdb_id, kpi_name, anomaly_count (number of anomalous rows in window), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (min timestamp among anomalies), latest_anomaly_timestamp (max timestamp among anomalies), max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window, global_p95, global_p5.\\nLimit returned list to at most 20 entries. Do not print full raw rows—only the aggregated fields requested." }

{
    "analysis": "We found that every (cmdb_id,kpi_name) pair flagged as anomalous within the incident window (1111 pairs) — many with anomaly_count=31 across the whole 30-minute window. The top anomalous pairs are dominated by Mysql01 metrics, plus some Tomcat, MG, IG entries. This widespread flagging suggests thresholds for many KPIs are degenerate (p95==p5==constant) or that the DB-related KPIs are persistently at extreme values. To localize the root cause, we must focus on resource-related KPIs (CPU, memory/heap, JVM, disk, network, IO, GC) and map anomalous KPIs to the predefined root cause reasons. We should next aggregate anomalies by component and by reason-category (keyword-based) to see which component shows resource faults, their earliest anomaly timestamps, and representative KPI names. This will narrow candidate root-cause components for trace/log follow-up.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv and the previously computed global thresholds (for allowed root-cause components), identify all anomalous metric rows in the incident window [1616491800,1616493600] (anomalous = value >= global_p95 OR value <= global_p5). For these anomalous rows, classify each row into one or more reason categories by keyword matching on kpi_name (case-insensitive). Use the following keyword->reason mapping (match if keyword appears anywhere in kpi_name):\\n- cpu, load -> \"high CPU usage\"\\n- memory, heap, HeapMemoryUsed, HeapMemory -> \"high memory usage\" (and additionally mark as \"JVM Out of Memory (OOM) Heap\" candidate if both HeapMemoryUsed and HeapMemoryMax exist for the same cmdb_id and at any timestamp HeapMemoryUsed/HeapMemoryMax >= 0.9)\\n- network, NETWORK, tcp, udp, packet -> \"network latency\" (and/or \"network packet loss\")\\n- disk, io, IO, filesystem, df, diskio -> \"high disk I/O read usage\" or \"high disk space usage\" (map to \"high disk I/O read usage\" if kpi_name contains io or read, else \"high disk space usage\" if contains space, filesystem, df)\\n- jvm, JVM, gc, gc_pause, ThreadCount, Thread -> \"high JVM CPU load\" or JVM-related (prefer \"high JVM CPU load\" if kpi_name contains CPU/JVM-CPU, else \"high JVM CPU load\" for jvm/gc/thread metrics)\\n- swap -> \"high memory usage\"\\nIf a kpi_name matches multiple keywords, include all applicable categories.\\nProduce a JSON-serializable report with: \\n1) For each cmdb_id (limit to top 20 by total anomalous row count) an object with: cmdb_id, total_anomalies (count of anomalous rows in window), distinct_anomalous_kpis (count), and per-reason entries (for each reason category that has at least one match) containing: reason_name, anomaly_count_for_reason, earliest_anomaly_timestamp_for_reason, latest_anomaly_timestamp_for_reason, sample_kpi_names (up to 5 distinct kpi_name examples).\\n2) Additionally, compute and return a separate list of cmdb_id values where both HeapMemoryUsed and HeapMemoryMax exist in metric data (for that cmdb_id) and the max of (HeapMemoryUsed/HeapMemoryMax) over the window >= 0.9 — list these as JVM_OOM_candidates with their earliest timestamp where ratio >=0.9 and the max ratio observed.\\nLimit all lists to at most 20 entries. Do not return raw full time series rows." }

{
    "analysis": "We have completed metric-level preprocessing and anomaly detection using global thresholds calculated from the full metric series. Results show pervasive anomalies across many components during the incident window, with Mysql01 and Mysql02 having the largest counts of anomalous metric points (dominant reasons: high disk I/O read usage, JVM-related anomalies, memory and CPU). Tomcat nodes also show many anomalies (disk I/O, disk space, network latency, JVM/memory). No JVM OOM candidates were found (HeapUsed/HeapMax < 0.9). Given multiple service-level candidates (MySQL and several Tomcats/MG/Redis), we must use trace data next to identify which faulty service is most downstream in request flows or which service latency/failure pattern aligns with the observed failure time. Trace analysis should use global trace thresholds (computed from full trace.csv) and then detect anomalies within the incident window to find which services/traces show abnormal latency or dropped row_counts corresponding to the failure time. This will help pick the most-likely root-cause component(s) for final log inspection.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Compute global thresholds for trace.csv first: for each (cmdb_id, trace_name) across the full trace.csv series calculate count, global P95, global P5, and mean (do NOT filter by the incident window yet). Then filter trace.csv to the incident window [1616491800,1616493600] and find anomalous rows where value >= global_p95 OR value <= global_p5. Return a compact JSON report with: \\n1) total number of distinct (cmdb_id, trace_name) pairs that have ≥1 anomaly in the window.\\n2) Top 20 anomalous (cmdb_id, trace_name) pairs by anomaly_count, each entry containing: cmdb_id, trace_name, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, latest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window, global_p95, global_p5.\\nLimit returned list to at most 20 entries and do not return full raw rows."}

{
    "analysis": "We computed global trace thresholds using the full trace series and detected 264 distinct anomalous (cmdb_id, trace_name) pairs in the incident window [1616491800,1616493600]. The top anomalous trace entries are mostly container-level (dockerA/B) and MG-level traces (MG01/MG02), with a few Tomcat entries (e.g., Tomcat01 trace.to_MG02.row_count). Many anomalies correspond to call-count drops (row_count) or latency spikes (duration_p95) on inter-service traces. To localize the root cause among the metric-identified faulty components (Mysql*, Tomcat*, MG*, IG*, Redis*, apache*), we should focus only on trace anomalies where the cmdb_id is one of the allowed root-cause components and on traces that represent calls between allowed components (trace.to_X / trace.from_X patterns). If a downstream allowed service in a trace sequence is anomalous and is the last faulty service in the trace chain, it becomes the likely root cause. At present we have not yet restricted trace anomalies to the allowed components nor extracted caller->callee relationships for anomalous traces — that is the next step.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From trace.csv, re-evaluate anomalies in window [1616491800,1616493600] using previously computed global thresholds (use full-series thresholds). Then filter anomalous trace rows to only those where cmdb_id is in the allowed root-cause components list: [apache01, apache02, Tomcat01, Tomcat02, Tomcat03, Tomcat04, MG01, MG02, IG01, IG02, Mysql01, Mysql02, Redis01, Redis02]. Produce two compact JSON outputs: \\n1) Per-component summary: for each allowed cmdb_id with ≥1 anomalous trace row, return cmdb_id, total_anomalous_trace_rows, distinct_anomalous_trace_names, earliest_anomaly_timestamp. Return top 20 components sorted by total_anomalous_trace_rows. \\n2) Inter-service anomalous trace map: for anomalous trace rows among allowed components whose trace_name contains 'to_' or 'from_' (case-insensitive), extract the called/peer component name from the trace_name (e.g., trace.to_MG02... => peer='MG02'), and return records with: caller_cmdb_id (the cmdb_id column), peer_component (extracted), trace_name, anomaly_count_for_this_pair (count of anomalous rows for this caller->peer trace in the window), earliest_anomaly_timestamp_for_pair. Return up to 50 such caller->peer mappings, sorted by anomaly_count descending. Do not return raw time series rows."}

{
    "analysis": "We ran metric, trace, and log analysis using global thresholds computed on the full series. Metrics flagged pervasive anomalies across many components; Mysql01 and Mysql02 had the largest counts of anomalous metric points (dominated by MySQL handler/read metrics and disk I/O-related KPIs). Trace anomalies concentrated on MG02 and MG01 (many anomalous row_count and duration_p95 traces), with inter-service mappings showing MG↔docker/Tomcat/IG interactions. Log analysis returned no error_count or zero row_count events in the window. We still cannot conclusively pick a single root cause because: multiple components have broad anomalous metrics, traces highlight MG nodes as heavily affected, and logs contain no clear error markers. According to the localization rules, we should now quantify the anomaly \"severity\" (how far a metric breached its global threshold) per component for resource-related KPIs (CPU, memory/heap, disk I/O/space, network, JVM) and identify the single largest severity fault (and its first occurrence timestamp). The most severe, earliest fault across allowed components will likely indicate the root cause component, occurrence time, and reason.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the previously computed global thresholds and the anomalous metric rows within [1616491800,1616493600], compute a severity score for each anomalous metric row as follows: if value >= global_p95, severity = (value - global_p95) / (abs(global_p95) if global_p95 != 0 else 1); if value <= global_p5, severity = (global_p5 - value) / (abs(global_p5) if global_p5 != 0 else 1). Map each kpi_name to one of the resource reason categories using keyword matching (case-insensitive): cpu/load -> high CPU usage; memory/heap/swap -> high memory usage; heap/HeapMemoryUsed+HeapMemoryMax (special handling) -> JVM Out of Memory (OOM) Heap candidate; network/tcp/udp/packet -> network latency or packet loss (keep as 'network latency' and also record presence of 'packet' keywords); disk/io/read/write/filesystem/df -> high disk I/O read usage or high disk space usage (if kpi_name contains 'FS'/'FSCapacity'/'FSUsed' etc. mark disk space). For every allowed root-cause component (apache01, apache02, Tomcat01–Tomcat04, MG01, MG02, IG01, IG02, Mysql01, Mysql02, Redis01, Redis02), compute: component, max_severity (maximum severity among its anomalous metric rows in the window), reason_category_of_max (the mapped reason for the KPI that produced max_severity), kpi_name_of_max, timestamp_of_max_severity, value_of_max, threshold_used (p95 or p5 as applicable), and whether this KPI is a JVM-Heap pair candidate (i.e., both HeapMemoryUsed and HeapMemoryMax exist for the component anywhere in full metric series). Return a JSON list of these component records sorted by max_severity descending, limited to top 20 components. Do not print full time series rows." }

{
    "analysis": "We have progressed through preprocessing, global threshold calculation, metric anomaly detection, trace anomaly detection, and log inspection. Metric analysis flagged pervasive anomalies across many components (Mysql01/Mysql02 dominant; Tomcat and MG nodes also heavily anomalous). Trace analysis identified MG01/MG02 and many inter-service caller->peer anomalies (row_count drops and duration_p95 spikes). Log analysis returned no error_count>0 or zero row_count events in the incident window. The most recent attempt to compute a per-component severity ranking (to pick the single most-severe, earliest fault) produced no returned output (the Executor cell completed but returned None), so we do not have the component severity results yet. To determine the root cause component, exact occurrence timestamp, and reason, we must obtain that component severity report (max severity per component, associated KPI and timestamp) so we can pick the single most significant fault and confirm via traces/logs. Because the previous cell likely executed but did not explicitly return values, we need the Executor to re-run the severity computation and explicitly return bounded outputs.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Re-run the component-severity computation and explicitly return the following bounded outputs (JSON-serializable) for the incident window [1616491800,1616493600]. Do not print full raw tables.\\n1) anomalous_rows_shape: a two-element tuple/list with (num_rows, num_columns) for anomalous metric rows in the window (anomalous = value >= global_p95 OR value <= global_p5 using previously computed full-series thresholds).\\n2) anomalous_sample: up to 10 sample anomalous rows (anomalous_rows.head(10)) with only these columns: timestamp, cmdb_id, kpi_name, value, global_p95, global_p5, breach_direction (\"upper\" if value>=global_p95 else \"lower\" if value<=global_p5). If there are fewer than 10 rows, return them all. If anomalous_rows is empty, set anomalous_sample to an empty list.\\n3) component_severity_list: for each allowed root-cause component [apache01, apache02, Tomcat01, Tomcat02, Tomcat03, Tomcat04, MG01, MG02, IG01, IG02, Mysql01, Mysql02, Redis01, Redis02], compute the maximum severity among its anomalous metric rows in the window where severity = (value - global_p95)/abs(global_p95) when value>=global_p95, or severity = (global_p5 - value)/abs(global_p5) when value<=global_p5 (use denominator 1 if the threshold is zero to avoid division by zero). For each component include: component (cmdb_id), max_severity (float), reason_category_of_max (one keyword-mapped category: high CPU usage / high memory usage / network latency / network packet loss / high disk I/O read usage / high disk space usage / high JVM CPU load / JVM Out of Memory (OOM) Heap as applicable), kpi_name_of_max, timestamp_of_max_severity, value_of_max, threshold_used (string \"p95\" or \"p5\"), jvm_heap_pair_exists (True/False indicating whether both HeapMemoryUsed and HeapMemoryMax exist for that component anywhere in the full metric series). Sort component_severity_list by max_severity descending and return only the top 20 components (or all if fewer).\\nIf anomalous_rows is empty, return anomalous_rows_shape and anomalous_sample empty and set component_severity_list to an empty list with an explanatory message.\\nReturn the results as a single JSON object containing the three fields above. Keep outputs compact and bounded." }

I reviewed the full analysis: metric anomalies are pervasive but are dominated by MySQL handler/read and disk-related KPIs on Mysql01 (highest anomalous point count and large breaches); trace anomalies show downstream services (MG01/MG02 and Tomcats) impacted with row_count drops and latency spikes; logs show no explicit errors. The earliest anomalies appear at the start of the incident window (timestamp 1616491800), which is 2021-03-23 17:30:00 in UTC+8. Therefore the most likely single root cause is a MySQL node experiencing high disk I/O read usage that caused downstream service degradation starting at 17:30.

